to be a campaign slogan in regular rotation (=E2=80=9CThis
is not a time for a caretaker, =E2=80=A6 this is time for a change-maker.=
=E2=80=9D Also: Expect to hear a lot more about the kitchen table.) We also=
 talked about Kamala=E2=80=99s future, a strategy to beat anyone from J.D. =
Vance to Bozo the Clown (hint: It involves a kitchen table), and what Repub=
licans are getting right.

The Zillion-Dollar Question

Tara Palmeri: Why do you think the Democrats lost?

Martin O=E2=80=99Malley: The question is essentially this: How, in a time o=
f economic recovery, could we have failed to win the economic argument at t=
he national level, while winning it in many other individual Senate, House,=
 and state legislative races? Somehow, we became disconnected from the kitc=
hen table issues that should be front and center in every election.

We have to change to win. This is not a time for a caretaker D.N.C. chair, =
this is time for a change-maker. And the good news for us is, what that cha=
nge involves, is really returning to our true selves=E2=80=94the party of w=
orking families, of the hopes, dreams, and aspirations of hard-working peop=
le who want to give their kids a better life.

