          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px;">
           <p style=3D"margin: 0; color: #000000; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 30px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 0;">Welcome back to The Best &a=
mp; The Brightest. I=E2=80=99m <b>Tara Palmeri</b>.<br/><br/>Happy Black Fr=
iday! I hope you had a wonderful Thanksgiving free of political blowups. (A=
t Chez Palmeri, we did have some random politics-adjacent skirmishes break =
out, but hey, that=E2=80=99s family.) Speaking of family infighting, the ra=
ce for Democratic National Committee chair seems to be the only thing Democ=
rats can talk about=E2=80=94besides that jaw-dropping, ass-covering <b>Plou=
ffe</b>/<b>O=E2=80=99Malley</b> <b>Dillon</b>/<b>Cutter</b>/<b>Fulks</b> in=
terview on <i>Pod Save America</i>. (Really, guys? You wouldn=E2=80=99t do =
<i>anything </i>differently?) <br/><br/>So in the spirit of fostering a wel=
l-informed electorate=E2=80=94in this case, of the few hundred Democrat Nat=
ional Committee members who will ultimately pick the chair=E2=80=94I=E2=80=
=99ve been vetting the D.N.C. chair candidates on my pod. Earlier this
week, I spoke to former congressman <b>Max Rose</b>, who hasn=E2=80=99t ann=
ounced his candidacy but is transparently flirting with a run. Then I spoke=
 to former Maryland governor <b>Martin O=E2=80=99Malley</b>, who officially=
 kicked off the race last week by announcing his own bid. Rose had no probl=
em blaming the <b>Harris</b> campaign for the Dems=E2=80=99 losses this cyc=
le; O=E2=80=99Malley, meanwhile, wouldn=E2=80=99t do so, even though a numb=
er of Democratic senate candidates outperformed the top of the ticket. <br/=
><br/>In any case, O=E2=80=99Malley shared some thoughts on Harris=E2=80=99=
s political future and, as you can imagine, came armed with talking points =
about Americans=E2=80=99 kitchen tables=E2=80=94which, as many of you likel=
y saw yesterday, is where the best family infighting happens. <br/><br/><i>=
But first, some news and notes from Dylan Byers=E2=80=A6</i><br/><br/></p><=
ul style=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-t=
op:0;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li>=
<i>Kaitlan=E2=80=99s homecoming</i>: CNN is sending <b>Kaitlan Collins </b>=
back to Washington, D.C., where she will pull double duty as chief White Ho=
use correspondent and host of her 9 p.m. show. The move will restore Kaitla=
n to her breakout role during the first Trump administration=E2=80=94before=
 <b>Chris Licht </b>made the ill-advised decision to position her as a morn=
ing show co-host with <b>Don Lemon</b>=E2=80=94and, frankly, it=E2=80=99s a=
 no-brainer: Kaitlan thrived as a D.C. political correspondent, is well-sou=
rced in Trumpworld, and always seemed reluctant to leave Washington in the =
first place. Now, in the second Trump era, she=E2=80=99s likely to become t=
he network=E2=80=99s biggest star.<br/><br/>Yes, it=E2=80=99s a lot more wo=
rk, but presumably her agents have negotiated a <i>far</i> higher salary co=
mmensurate with the additional duties. And it also positions
her well for a future where the primetime lineup means less and less. The b=
ig question, of course, is when Collins=E2=80=94a wunderkind stuck in an in=
dustry in terminal decline=E2=80=94will become compelled to opt out of the =
old world and try her hand at her own <b>Bari Weiss</b>/Don Lemon/<b>Ben Sh=
apiro</b>-type enterprise. She has the star power and access to the capital=
, but it=E2=80=99s an open question as to when she realizes that her future=
 outside CNN is brighter than within.<br/><br/>On a related note, it=E2=80=
=99s hard not to see Kaitlan=E2=80=99s expanded assignment as an unfortunat=
e reflection of CNN=E2=80=99s <i>in</i>ability to foster new talent. In the=
ory, network talent chief <b>Amy Entelis </b>should have spent the past sev=
eral years grooming a new generation of Kaitlans. Instead, the network hasn=
=E2=80=99t created <i>any </i>new stars since <b>Jeff</b> <b>Zucker </b>lef=
t the building. (Yes, he hired Kaitlan, too). =E2=80=94<i>Dylan Byers</i></=
li></ul>
          </td>
